    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"782416\">Thobias Rex Smite</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/How.20to.20perform.20induction.20over.20two.20steps.20back/near/483988264\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Now I was not interested in letting <code>n = 0</code>, since the theorem becomes uninteresting:</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That sounds like quite a bad reason for not including <code>n=0</code>! Indeed I I'd say that the vast majority of theorems proved by induction are not interesting at n=0. Surely the only reason you shouldn't include n=0 is when the claim is <em>false</em>? If you explicitly add n&gt;0 as a hypothesis then your theorem becomes more annoying to use because users need to supply this unnecessary extra hypotheses whenever they apply it.</p>",
